{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505563"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:32:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:32:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2455"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2455"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.61,0.04,0.17,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2455"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42267"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2455"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2455"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27297"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2011"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2045"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42495"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43159"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42267"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with an acutely swollen and tender right knee. She states that it developed over the last few hours and has become so bad that she can barely walk on it now. Her medical history includes gout (with regular flares over the last 10 years), hypertension and dyslipidaemia. Her medications include 300mg daily allopurinol, perindopril and atorvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she appears well. Her pulse rate is 98/min, blood pressure 120/70mmHg, SpO2 99% on room air and temperature of 37.3\u00b0C. Her right knee is swollen and erythematous with no evidence of trauma.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In regards to her allopurinol, which one of the following is the most appropriate action to take during this acute episode?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stop allopurinol immediately","Continue allopurinol at the same dose","Lower the dose of allopurinol to 50mg per day","Increase the dose of allopurinol to 400mg per day","Start weaning her allopurinol down"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case describes an acute gout attack. The woman has a history of gout and has had flares in the past. Investigations such as a joint aspiration and joint x-ray would likely be sought in this case to confirm it is in fact a gout flare and not septic arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe recommendation around the use of allopurinol in acute gout attacks has changed over the past 10 years. Currently the recommendation provided by the Therapeutic Guidelines is that patients on urate lowering therapy, such as allopurinol, \u003Cstrong\u003Eshould NOT change their current regime \u003C/strong\u003Eduring a gout flare as an increase/decrease or stopping the medication can alter the serum uric acid levels and prolong or worsen the attack. This is an important counselling point to reinforce in patients on these medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStarting or \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreasing urate lowering therapy\u003C/strong\u003E (eg. allopurinol) is associated with precipitation of acute gout flares, thus increasing the dose would risk of a prolonged attack or another attack in the short-term future. When starting/increasing allopurinol colchicine, an NSAID or prednisolone should be used alongside it to reduce the risk of this.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStopping, decreasing or weaning allopurinol\u003C/strong\u003E during an acute flare would result in an increased uric acid level, hence losing the therapeutic effect of the medication and worsening the attack. There is also a risk the medication will not be started again on discharge, putting the patient at risk of further flares without urate lowering therapy on board. Furthemore, evidence supports now starting allopurinol during acute flares is safe. But it should be commenced with flare prophylaxis medication as well, as mentioned above.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management options for her acute attack include NSAIDs, steroids or colchicine. Her long-term management with allopurinol should be titrated to target urate levels of \u0026lt;0.36 mmol/L in patients without tophi and \u0026lt;0.30 mmol/L in patients with tophi.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Allopurinol is safe to be started during an acute gout flare alongside flare prophylaxis medications","Allopurinol doses should not be changed during an acute flare","Urate lowering therapy should be titrated to get a serum uric acid level of \u003C0.36 mmol/L in patients with no tophi and \u003C0.30 mmol/L in patients with tophi present"],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd. Gout [online]. 2019. Available at: https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/viewTopic?topicfile=gout\u0026guidelineName=Rheumatology\u0026topicNavigation=navigateTopic#toc_d1e232.","Allopurinol. In: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd [online]. 2021. Available at: https://amhonline-amh-net-au.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/chapters/rheumatological-drugs/drugs-gout/xanthine-oxidase-inhibitors/allopurinol.","Robinson PC, Stamp LK. The management of gout: Much has changed. Aust Fam Physician. 2016;45(5):299-302. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2016/may/the-management-of-gout-much-has-changed/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27297"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2455"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27297"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-05T15:44:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-02-05T15:44:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2455"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42267"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationsh